[{"type":"{{","value":[["pagebanner"]]},"\n",{"type":"{{","value":[["itinerary"]]},"\n",{"type":"'''","value":["Columbia to Patagonia overland"]}," is a journey ",{"type":"'''","value":["along the Andes"]}," across ",{"type":"[[","value":[["South America"]]},". This route starts from the sunny beaches of the Caribbean and crosses ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Colombia"]]},", ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Ecuador"]]},", ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Peru"]]},", ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Bolivia"]]},",",{"type":"[[","value":[["Chile"]]}," and ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Argentina"]]}," before terminating in the icy shores of the Antarctic Ocean. Crossing 6 countries, spanning over 10,000 kilometers, this is one of the ultimate overland journeys in the world.\n\n",{"type":"==","value":["Understand"]},"\nThis trip can be divided up three similar sized segments each with its own characteristic. \n\n",{"type":"*","value":["Cartagena to Lima (4000 km)- Tropical highland and rainforest (Humid and warm to hot all year around)"]},{"type":"*","value":["Lima to Santiago (3800 km)- Altiplano and Atacama Desert (Extremely dry and large day\/night temperature variations)"]},{"type":"*","value":["Santiago to Patagonia (3400 km taking RN40)- Temperate to sub-arctic (Pleasant marine climate)"]},"\n",{"type":"===","value":["Bus classes"]},"\n\nAlthough it is entirely possible to go from one end of South America to the other in chicken buses it is the balance of cost and comfort that makes overlanding fun. To the purpose, long distance buses fall under 3 general comfort levels: Semicama, Cama, Cama Suite. These names tend to shift from country to country.\n\n",{"type":"{|","value":[["border=\"1\" class=\"wikitable\""],["|+ South America bus classes"],["! Country"],["! Semicama (Half bed)"],["! Cama (Bed)"],["! Cama Suite (Bed Suite)"],["|-"],["! Argentina"],["| Semicama  40°"],["| Cama-Ejecutivo 55°"],["| Cama Suite 85°"],["|-"],["! Chile"],["| Semi Cama 60°"],["| Cama 65°"],["| Cama Premium 90°"],["|-"],["! Peru"],["| Semicama\/Imperial\/Especial  40-50°"],["| Cama\/VIP 70-75°"],["| Super Cama\/Super VIP\/Sofá Cama 90°"],["|-"],["! Brazil"],["| Executivo 40°"],["| Semi-Leito 55°"],["| Leito 80°"]]},"\n\n",{"type":"===","value":["Language"]},"\n",{"type":"'''","value":[{"type":"[[","value":[["Spanish phrasebook"],["Spanish"]]}]}," is the official language in all countries on this trip.\n\n",{"type":"===","value":["Climate"]},"\nClimate along the Pacific coast is mainly affected by latitude with the temperature colder the further south you go. In Colombia and Equador, it is tropical. Once into Peru, the humidity starts to decline. South of Lima, the environment becomes very arid. The Atacama Desert, known as the driest place in the world, lies in Southern Peru and Northern Chile. Around Santiago desert gives way to subtropical rainforests. In Patagonia, climate gradually shifts from temperate to to sub-polar, with evergreens gradually dominating the landscape.\n\nIn the Andes, altitude matters more than latitude. The rule of thumb is that temperature decreases by 6 degrees Celsius for every 1,000-meter gain in elevation. Much the trip in Peru crosses the Altiplano, where altitude hovers around 4,000 meters. Daytime temperature is pleasant while nights can be freezing.\n\n",{"type":"==","value":["Prepare"]},"\n\n",{"type":"==","value":["Get in"]},"\n",{"type":"===","value":["By plane"]},"\n",{"type":"[[","value":[["Bogota"]]},", ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Lima"]]}," and ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Santiago de Chile"],["Santiago"]]}," are the principal airports for those flying in from outside of South America.\n\n",{"type":"[[","value":[["Quito"]]},", ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Medellin"]]}," and ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Cusco"]]}," are more useful for those flying in from other parts of South America.\n\nIn Northern Patagonia, ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Puerto Montt"]]}," and ",{"type":"[[","value":[["San Carlos de Bariloche"]]}," are good airports to travel to, while in Southern Patagonia, ",{"type":"[[","value":[["El Calafate"]]}," ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Punta Arenas"]]},", ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Rio Grande"]]}," and ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Ushuaia"]]}," are good airports to fly back from.\n\n",{"type":"[[","value":[["Uyuni"]]}," has an airport for those unwilling to endure the hardship of Bolivian roads.\n\n",{"type":"===","value":["By boat"]},"\n",{"type":"[[","value":[["Cartagena (Colombia)"],["Cartagena"]]},", is the principle port between ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Colombia"]]}," and ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Panama"]]},". This is the only way to get pass the Darien Gap without flying.\n\nIt is ",{"type":"'''","value":["theoretically"]}," possible to arrive by boat from the Amazon. Starting from ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Belem"]]}," take the ferry to ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Manaus"]]}," (5 days) then change ferry to ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Iquitos"]]}," (5 days). Once at Iquitos, three options existː ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Yurimaguas"]]}," (2.5 days), ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Pucallpa"]]}," (4 days) and ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Coca"]]}," (8 days). All three cities have motorable roads to the west of the Andes. \n\n",{"type":"===","value":["By bus"]},"\nSince every major city west of the Andes has been covered in the Routes section below, the only remaining starting points lie far beyond the Andes on the eastern Atlantic coast. These bus rides are epic journeys in and of themselves.\n\nFrom ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Sao Paulo"]]},", ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Brazil"]]},", Ormeño runs a bus to ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Lima"]]}," on the Interoceanic Highway (108 hours). Get off at Cusco to save 21 hours.\n\nFrom ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Buenos Aires"]]},", ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Argentina"]]},", buses to ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Lima"]]}," (72 hours), ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Santiago de Chile"],["Santiago"]]}," (19-20 hours hours), ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Bariloche"]]}," (20-23 hours) and ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Rio Gallegos"]]}," (36 hours).\n\n",{"type":"==","value":["Route"]},"\n",{"type":"{{","value":[["Mapframe"],["-27.0"],["-73.0"],["zoom=5"],["height=2100"],["width=400"],["layer=R"],["name=South America"]]},"\n",{"type":"===","value":[" Colombia "]},"\n\n",{"type":"{{","value":[["listing"],["name=",{"type":"[[","value":[["Cartagena (Colombia)"],["Cartagena"]]}],["lat=10.4237"],["long=-75.5244"],["content=Caribean port city. Start of this journey."]]},"\n\n",{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Cartagena (Colombia)"],["Cartagena"]]}," to ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Medellin"]]}]},"\n",{"type":"{{","value":[["listing"],["name=",{"type":"[[","value":[["Medellin"]]}],["lat=6.242"],["long=-75.578"]]},"\n\n",{"type":"*","value":[{"type":"*","value":[" Day trip to El Peñón de Guatapé"]}]},{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Medellin"]]}," to ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Bogotá"]]}]},"\n",{"type":"{{","value":[["listing"],["name=",{"type":"[[","value":[["Bogotá"]]}],["lat=4.5973"],["long=-74.0769"]]},"\n\n",{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Bogota"]]}," to ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Cali"]]}]},"\n",{"type":"{{","value":[["listing"],["name=",{"type":"[[","value":[["Pasto"]]}],["lat=3.4355"],["long=-76.5280"]]},"\n\n",{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Pasto"]]}," to ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Ipiales"]]}]},{"type":"{{","value":[["see"],["name=",{"type":"[[","value":[["Las Lajas Sanctuary"]]}],["lat=0.8049"],["long=-77.5857"],["content=Basilica straddling a canyon. 20-min from Ipiales by taxi."]]},"\n\n",{"type":"===","value":[" Ecuador "]},"\nTulcan is a border town. Be careful with money changers as some may be crooks.\n",{"type":"*","value":[{"type":"[[","value":[["Tulcan"]]}," to ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Quito"]]}," (5 hours)"]},{"type":"*","value":[{"type":"[[","value":[["Quito"]]}," to ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Trujillo (Peru)"],["Trujillo"]]}]},"\n",{"type":"===","value":[" Peru "]},"\n",{"type":"*","value":["at ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Trujillo (Peru)"],["Trujillo"]]}]},"\n",{"type":"{{","value":[["listing"],["name=",{"type":"[[","value":[["Trujillo (Peru)"],["Trujillo"]]}],["lat=-8.111"],["long=-79.027"]]}," is sizable city to stop in northern Peru. \nThere are 3 near by sites of interest: The beaches of ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Huanchaco"]]},", Pyramid of the Sun and the Moon and Chan Chan.\n\n",{"type":"[[","value":[["Trujillo (Peru)"],["Trujillo"]]}," to ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Lima"]]}," takes 9 hours. ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Caral"]]}," is 6 hours into the trip.\n\n",{"type":"{{","value":[["listing"],["name=",{"type":"[[","value":[["Lima"]]}],["lat=-12.043333"],["long=-77.028333"],["content=Capital of Peru. This one third of this journey."]]},"\n\n",{"type":"*","value":[{"type":"[[","value":[["Lima"]]}," to ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Cusco"]]}," (21 hours)"]},{"type":"*","value":["Alternatively, break up this trip into smaller segments:"]},{"type":"*","value":[{"type":"*","value":[{"type":"[[","value":[["Lima"]]}," to ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Ica"]]}," (5 hours) - Spend the night in ",{"type":"{{","value":[["see"],["name=",{"type":"[[","value":[["Huacachina"]]}," Oasis"],["alt="],["url="],["email="],["address="],["lat=-14.08754"],["long=-75.76298"],["directions="],["phone="],["tollfree="],["fax="],["hours="],["price="],["content="]]},"."]}]},"\n\n",{"type":"*","value":[{"type":"*","value":[{"type":"[[","value":[["Ica"]]}," to ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Nazca"]]}," (2 hours)"]}]},"\nFrom ",{"type":"{{","value":[["see"],["name=",{"type":"[[","value":[["Nazca"]]}],["lat=-14.8275"],["long=-74.9370"]]}," you can see the surrounding Nazca lines and the lost city of Ciudad Perdida de Cahuachi.\n\n",{"type":"*","value":[{"type":"*","value":[{"type":"[[","value":[["Nazca"]]}," to ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Cusco"]]}," (14.5 hours, night bus)"]}]},{"type":"*","value":[{"type":"*","value":[{"type":"*","value":[{"type":"[[","value":[["Nazca"]]}," to ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Arequipa"]]}," (10 hours)"]}]}]},"\n",{"type":"{{","value":[["listing"],["name=",{"type":"[[","value":[["Arequipa"]]}],["lat=-16.4027"],["long=-71.5375"]]},"\n\n",{"type":"*","value":[{"type":"*","value":[{"type":"*","value":[{"type":"[[","value":[["Arequipa"]]}," to ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Cusco"]]}," (9 hours)"]}]}]},"\n",{"type":"{{","value":[["listing"],["name=",{"type":"[[","value":[["Cusco"]]}],["lat=-13.520608"],["long=-71.967129"],["content=Ancient capital of the Incas."]]},"\n\n",{"type":"{{","value":[["see"],["name=",{"type":"[[","value":[["Machu Picchu"]]}],["lat=-13.163797"],["long=-72.545814"],["content=Sacred city of the Incas."]]},"\n\n",{"type":"*","value":[{"type":"*","value":["Ollantaytambo"]}]},{"type":"*","value":[{"type":"[[","value":[["Cusco"]]}," to ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Puno"]]}]},"\n",{"type":"{{","value":[["sleep"],["name=",{"type":"[[","value":[["Puno"]]}],["lat=-15.85"],["long=-70.02"],["content=Sacred city of the Incas."]]},"\n\n",{"type":"*","value":[{"type":"*","value":["Cruise ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Lake Titicaca"]]}]}]},{"type":"*","value":[{"type":"[[","value":[["Puno"]]}," to ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Desaguadero"]]}]},"\n",{"type":"===","value":[" Bolivia "]},"\n",{"type":"*","value":["Border to ",{"type":"[[","value":[["La Paz"]]}]},{"type":"*","value":[{"type":"*","value":[{"type":"[[","value":[["Tiwanaku"]]}," (Gate of the Sun)"]}]},{"type":"*","value":[{"type":"*","value":[{"type":"[[","value":[["Isla del Sol"]]}," "]}]},{"type":"*","value":[{"type":"[[","value":[["La Paz"]]}," via ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Oruno"]]}," to ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Uyuni"]]}]},{"type":"*","value":[{"type":"*","value":["Possible detour to ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Potasi"]]}]}]},"\n",{"type":"{{","value":[["see"],["name=",{"type":"[[","value":[["Salar de Uyuni"]]}],["lat=-20.336"],["long=-67.353"],["content=Largest salt flat in the world."]]},"\n\nFrom here on is a 3 day jeep ride to ",{"type":"[[","value":[["San Pedro de Atacama"]]},".\n\nFirst day you will be traveling on the salt flat and spend the night in San Juan. The sights are the cactus island, train graveyard.\n\n",{"type":"{{","value":[["sleep"],["name=",{"type":"[[","value":[["San Juan"]]}],["lat=-20.898839"],["long=-67.766869"],["content=Tiny road side town."]]},"\n\nSecond day you will be traveling parallel along the Chilean border through Desierto de Siloli and spend the night by Laguna Colorada. The major sights are Laguna Hedionda, Árbol de Piedra.\n\n",{"type":"{{","value":[["see"],["name=",{"type":"[[","value":[["Laguna Colorada"]]}],["lat=-22.208261"],["long=-67.774100"],["content=Pink lake famous for its Andean flamingoes"]]},"\n\nThird day you will be traveling in the Eduardo Avaroa National Reserve before crossing the border to Chile at Hito Cajon. The major sights are Sol de Mañana, Termas de Polques hot springs and Laguna Verde.\n\n\n\n",{"type":"===","value":[" Chile "]},"\n\n",{"type":"{{","value":[["listing"],["name=",{"type":"[[","value":[["San Pedro de Atacama"]]}],["lat=-22.909673"],["long=-68.201571"],["content=Good place to rest and recuperate after the road trip. The lunar landscapes of Valle de la Luna is just outside the city."]]},"\n\n",{"type":"*","value":[{"type":"[[","value":[["Calama"]]}]},"\n",{"type":"{{","value":[["listing"],["name=",{"type":"[[","value":[["Antofagasta"]]}],["lat=-23.6465"],["long=-70.3962"]]},"\n\n",{"type":"*","value":[{"type":"*","value":["Possible detour to ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Pampa del Tamarugal"]]}]}]},{"type":"*","value":[{"type":"[[","value":[["Antofagasta"]]}," to ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Santiago de Chile"],["Santiago"]]}," - long bus ride on Highway 5"]},"\n",{"type":"{{","value":[["listing"],["name=",{"type":"[[","value":[["Santiago de Chile"],["Santiago"]]}],["lat=-33.4436"],["long=-70.6496"],["content=Capital of Chile. Two thirds of this journey."]]},"\n\n",{"type":"*","value":[{"type":"[[","value":[["Santiago de Chile"],["Santiago"]]}," to ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Puerto Montt"]]}," take 12 hours. ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Valdivia"]]}," or ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Frutillar"]]}," are good stop overs to break up the journey."]},"\n",{"type":"{{","value":[["listing"],["name=",{"type":"[[","value":[["Valdivia"]]}],["lat=-39.8139"],["long=-73.2458"],["content=Sea side German town."]]},"\n\n",{"type":"{{","value":[["listing"],["name=Puerto Octay\/",{"type":"[[","value":[["Frutillar"]]},"\/llanquihue\/",{"type":"[[","value":[["Puerto Varas"]]}],["lat=-40.973"],["long=-72.881"],["content=German town by Lake Llanquihue."]]},"\n\n",{"type":"===","value":[" Patagonia "]},"\n",{"type":"*","value":["Due to the difficulty of the terrain and the amorphous nature of the southern Chile-Argentina border, traveling overland in Patagonia requires at least 1 border crossing. "]},"\n",{"type":"====","value":[" Northern Patagonia (Chile option) "]},"\n\nThe starting point here is the port city of ",{"type":"{{","value":[["listing"],["name=",{"type":"[[","value":[["Puerto Montt"]]}],["lat=-41.466667"],["long=-72.933333"]]},". From here, 2 options exist:\n\n1. Take the Navimag ferry to ",{"type":"{{","value":[["listing"],["name=",{"type":"[[","value":[["Puerto Natales"]]}],["lat=-51.721"],["long=-72.499"]]}," (400 USD 4 days\/3 nights). This is the most straight forward option. The ferry travels through Chilean fjords en route. Note, ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Puerto Natales"]]}," is close to ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Torres del Paine"]]},". You will see the Southern Patagonia sights in the reverse order (south to north) as they are listed.\n\n2. Overland on the ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Carretera Austral"]]}," (Southern Road) to ",{"type":"{{","value":[["listing"],["name=Villa O'Higgins"],["lat=-48.469"],["long=-72.559"]]},". This is the more difficult option. Most of trip will be on pot holed roads with occasional ferry crossings. Towns are few in number and far in between. Taking this road all the way down will arrive at Villa O'Higgins. From there on it is a ferry ride across the border on Lago San Martin. From there on is a 20km hike until Laguna del Desierto. Taking another ferry across the lake will get you to a road that leads to ",{"type":"[[","value":[["El Chaltén"]]},".\n\n",{"type":"====","value":[" Northern Patagonia (Argentina option) "]},"\n\nThe starting point here is the beautiful mountain resort town of ",{"type":"{{","value":[["listing"],["name=",{"type":"[[","value":[["Bariloche"]]}],["lat=-41.15"],["long=-71.3"]]},".\n\n",{"type":"*","value":["Arriving from ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Puerto Montt"]]}," or ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Puerto Varas"]]}," takes 4 hours by bus or 1-2 days by ferry\/bus combination."]},"\n",{"type":"*","value":["Arriving from ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Buenos Aires"]]}," takes 21 hours by bus. "]},"\nLinger a few days at ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Bariloche"]]}," before heading south on the famous Ruta 40 (RN40) to ",{"type":"[[","value":[["El Chaltén"]]}," (24 hours in a cramped mini bus).\n\n",{"type":"====","value":[" Southern Patagonia (Chile and Argentina) "]},"\n\nThe three big ticket sights starting from north to south are: \n\n",{"type":"{{","value":[["see"],["name=Monte Fitz Roy"],["address="],["lat=-49.271278"],["long=-73.043222"],["directions=near ",{"type":"[[","value":[["El Chaltén"]]}],["content=many day hikes in the surrounding area"]]},"\n\n",{"type":"{{","value":[["see"],["name=Glaciar Perito Moreno"],["address="],["lat=-50.483333"],["long=-73.05"],["directions=near ",{"type":"[[","value":[["El Calafate"]]}],["content=massive glacier"]]},"\n\n",{"type":"{{","value":[["see"],["name=",{"type":"[[","value":[["Torres del Paine"]]}],["address="],["lat=-51"],["long=-73"],["directions=north of ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Puerto Natales"]]}],["content=hike famous W trek (4-5 days) or full circuit (7-9 days)"]]},"\n\n",{"type":"===","value":[" Tierra del Fuego "]},"\nFor those who seek to go as far south as possible. There are 3 destinations from north to south:\n\n",{"type":"{{","value":[["listing"],["name=",{"type":"[[","value":[["Punta Arenas"]]}],["address="],["lat=-53.16667"],["long=-70.93333"],["directions="],["content=Southern most city on the South American continent"]]},"\n\n",{"type":"{{","value":[["listing"],["name=",{"type":"[[","value":[["Ushuaia"]]}],["address="],["lat=-54.8"],["long=-68.3"],["directions="],["content=Southern most city in ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Argentina"]]}]]},"\n\n",{"type":"{{","value":[["listing"],["name=",{"type":"[[","value":[["Puerto Williams"]]}],["url="],["email="],["address="],["lat=-54.933333"],["long=-67.616667"],["directions="],["content=Southern most city in ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Chile"]]}]]},"\n\nFrom ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Punta Arenas"]]},", take a there is a ",{"type":"[","value":["http:\/\/www.tabsa.cl\/portal\/index.php\/en\/services\/55-punta-arenas-puerto-williams-crossing 30 hour ferry"]}," to ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Ushuaia"]]},".\n\nAlternatively, there are bus connecting ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Puerto Natales"]]}," and ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Rio Gallegos"]]}," with ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Rio Grande"]]},". From ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Rio Grande"]]}," there is another bus to ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Ushuaia"]]},".\n\n",{"type":"==","value":["Stay safe"]},"\nEven through violence in ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Colombia"]]}," has greatly subsided in recent years, the section between ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Cali"]]}," to ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Ipiales"]]}," is still not quite safe. Avoid night buses or being outside at night.\n\n",{"type":"==","value":["Go next"]},"\n",{"type":"===","value":[" Alternative ways back "]},"\n",{"type":"*","value":[" Head to ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Rio Gallegos"]]}," for a 36-hour (Cama Suite) bus north to ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Buenos Aires"]]}]},{"type":"*","value":[" Visit ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Iguaçu Falls"]]}]},{"type":"*","value":[" Continue to ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Sao Paulo"]]}]},{"type":"*","value":[" From ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Sao Paulo"]]}," take 108-hour bus across the Amazon to ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Lima"]]}]},"\n",{"type":"{{","value":[["outlineitinerary"]]},"\n",{"type":"{{","value":[["geo"],["-11.4"],["-68.2"],["zoom=3"]]}]